<TITLE> Putin urges West not to back Kosovo independence </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SOFIA, Jan 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Russian President Vladimir Putin said on Friday any unilateral recognition of Kosovo's independence by Western states would be "illegal and immoral". Russia opposes granting independence to Serbia's breakaway province without Belgrade's consent. It has accused the West of encouraging Kosovo's leaders to take an uncompromising stand on the issue by promising to back their unilateral move. "A unilateral declaration of independence and support for that process from other members of the international community would be an illegal and immoral solution," Putin said during a visit to Bulgaria. "We believe negotiations on the Kosovo settlement should be continued in order to find a compromise," Putin told a joint news conference with Bulgaria's President Georgi Parvanov. Russia, a veto-wielding permanent member of the U.N. Security Council, has blocked Western attempts to have Kosovo's independence blessed by the United Nations. Moscow says a unilateral declaration of independence by the mainly ethnic Albanian province would destabilise the Balkan region and fuel separatism elsewhere. Parvanov said Bulgaria, a new member of NATO and of the European Union, backed the majority EU view that Kosovo should become independent but he also urged caution. "We believe it is very important to achieve unity in the European Union so the Kosovo problem does not become a dividing line in the Union," he said. "We have more than once warned about the risks of premature solutions to this problem
